<TITLE> China says Japan violated sovereignty over islands </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Oct 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - China accused Japan on Tuesday of infringing on its sovereignty when the Japanese Coast Guard warned a boat carrying Chinese activists not to approach disputed islands in the East China Sea. The eight uninhabited islands, claimed by China as the Diaoyu islands and by Japan as the Senkaku isles, are thought to lie near oil and gas reserves and have long been a source of friction between Beijing and Tokyo. Japan's Coast Guard said on Sunday a boat hoisting a Chinese flag briefly entered waters claimed by Japan near the disputed islands, but left after a warning from a Coast Guard patrol boat. "(It) violates international law, infringes on China's sovereignty and is illegal. The Chinese side resolutely opposes" the warning, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Liu Jianchao told a regular news briefing when asked to comment on the incident. "The Diaoyu isles have been an inseparable part of Chinese territory since ancient times. The Chinese side has indisputable sovereignty over the Diaoyu isles," Liu added. Kyodo news agency, quoting a Hong Kong-based activist group, said the vessel was carrying four Chinese people protesting at Japan's control over the island chain, which is also claimed by Taiwan. Disputes over the islands flare up periodically. In February this year, China expressed "extreme dissatisfaction" and summoned a Japanese diplomat over Tokyo's complaints about a Chinese research ship that had approached the islands. In 2004, Japan arrested and deported seven Chinese activists after they landed on one of the islands. Relations between China and Japan, long plagued by disputes over their wartime past as well as territorial feuds and mutual mistrust over military ambitions, deteriorated sharply when Junichiro Koizumi was Japanese prime minister from 2001-2006, partly because of his visits to a controversial war shrine. Relations improved after Koizumi's successor, Shinzo Abe, took office and visited Beijing in October 2